üìã RECOMMENDATIONS
==================

‚úÖ Best Practices:
   1. Use ask() for operations that require a response (queries, calculations)
   2. Use tell() for fire-and-forget operations (logging, notifications)
   3. Cache actor refs to avoid repeated lookups
   4. Use parallel ask() calls when querying multiple services
   5. Consider timeouts for ask() operations in production

üîß Code Examples:
   // Create actor ref once:
   let location = registry.lookup("database_service").await?;
   let conn = registry.get_connection(peer_addr).await?;

   // Sequential queries:
   let result1 = conn.ask(query1).await?;
   let result2 = conn.ask(query2).await?;

   // Parallel queries:
   let (r1, r2) = tokio::join!(
       conn1.ask(query1),
       conn2.ask(query2)
   );

‚ö†Ô∏è  NOTE: Current ask() implementation returns mock responses.
   In production, implement proper request-response correlation.

KEY FINDING:
  rkyv::from_bytes::<RegistryMessage>() ALLOCATES entire message
  ‚Üí Allocates: RegistryMessage enum + all Vec<u8> fields
  ‚Üí Per-message cost: ~1KB (varies by message type)

EXPECTED OPTIMIZED:
  rkyv::access::<RegistryMessage>() returns &Archived<RegistryMessage>
  ‚Üí Zero-copy reference into network buffer
  ‚Üí NO allocations for message body

EXPECTED REDUCTION:
  ~90%+ reduction in body allocations (much larger than header win)
  Dramatic impact on high-throughput distributed systems
